-- в”Ђв”Ђ Modal в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Modal is a serverless cloud platform that lets developers run Python-native AI, ML and data workloads, including GPU jobs, with per-second billing and no infrastructure management.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free ($30/month in compute credits)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2021, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Approximately 100-150 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New York, New York, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Modal Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Modal review 2026: the serverless GPU and CPU cloud for AI and ML workloads. Compare features, per-second pricing, and top Modal alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Modal is a serverless cloud compute platform built for running AI, machine learning, and data-intensive workloads, including GPU-accelerated jobs, without managing servers, containers, or Kubernetes clusters. The company, Modal Labs, Inc., was founded in January 2021 by Erik Bernhardsson, a former engineering leader at Spotify and Better.com and the creator of open-source tools Luigi and Annoy, alongside co-founder and CTO Akshat Bubna. Modal is headquartered in New York City with additional offices in San Francisco and Stockholm, and had roughly 100 to 150 employees as of 2026. The company raised an $87 million Series B in September 2025 led by Lux Capital with participation from existing investors Redpoint Ventures and Amplify Partners, pushing its valuation to about $1.1 billion and unicorn status. Architecturally, Modal's core innovation is a Python-native developer experience: instead of writing Dockerfiles and Kubernetes manifests, developers decorate ordinary Python functions (for example with @app.function()) and Modal handles containerization, scaling, and scheduling automatically, spinning up compute in seconds and scaling to zero when idle. Modal bills by the second for CPU, GPU and memory usage, which the company positions as the finest-grained billing in the serverless GPU category. Core features include serverless GPU functions supporting chips like A10G, A100 and H100, scheduled and event-triggered jobs, persistent storage volumes, web endpoint deployment for serving models and APIs, sandboxed code execution, and fast cold-start container images. Pricing is usage-based: a free Starter tier includes $30 per month in compute credits, three workspace seats, and modest concurrency limits; the Team plan costs $250 per month plus compute usage and includes $100 in monthly credits, unlimited seats, and higher concurrency; Enterprise pricing is custom. Illustrative per-hour GPU rates include A10G from about $1.10/hour, A100 from about $3.72/hour, and H100 from about $4.29/hour, though actual costs depend on per-second usage. Modal's target audience is AI/ML engineers, data scientists, and startups that need to run training, fine-tuning, batch inference, and data pipelines without dedicated infrastructure or DevOps teams. Its main competitors include Replicate, Banana, RunPod, Baseten, AWS SageMaker, and traditional Kubernetes-based ML platforms. Modal differentiates itself through its lightweight Python SDK, per-second billing granularity, and fast cold starts, aiming to remove the operational overhead typically associated with GPU infrastructure.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'c5f50ff9-292d-461f-9877-3ee54d35032f';

